Eruptive Activity on the Western Flank of Piton de la Fournaise (La Réunion Island, Indian Ocean): Insights on Magma Transfer, Storage and Evolution at an Oceanic Volcanic Island

, , , , , , , , , , ... Show more
Journal of Petrology, Volume 60, Issue 9, September 2019, Pages 1717–1752, https://doi.org/10.1093/petrology/egz045
Published:
18 October 2019
Article history
  • PDF
  • Split View
  • Cite
  • Permissions Icon Permissions
  • Share Icon Share

Abstract

Petrological and geochemical (major element, trace element, Sr–Nd isotope) data for recent (<5 kyr old) basalts that sporadically erupt on the western flank of Piton de la Fournaise (PdF), one of the most active volcanoes on Earth, allow the tracking of magma transfer and evolution from mantle to crustal depths. In the western peripheral area of PdF we document the broadly synchronous eruptions of (1) primitive olivine and olivine–clinopyroxene transitional basalts with tholeiitic affinity that are closely associated in space with (2) transitional olivine basalts with alkaline affinity, and (3) hybrid lavas, intermediate between the ‘alkaline’ and the ‘tholeiitic’ end-members. The composition of the latter overlaps with that of the lavas frequently erupted from the conduit system feeding the main summit cone. AlphaMELTS modelling, and fluid inclusion and clinopyroxene barometry, constrain the conditions of magma storage at 10–30 km, and the ascent of magma from the upper mantle to the shallow crustal plumbing system. Variable degrees of mantle melting, together with minor source heterogeneity and contamination with cumulate-derived partial melts, contribute to the diversity of PdF magmas. However, all these processes do not represent the dominant factors that produce the large variability we found in major element composition. Indeed, the composition of basalts erupted from PdF peripheral centers is strongly controlled by polybaric olivine–clinopyroxene fractionation at pressures higher than 3 kbar. Crystal textures and geochemical modelling suggest that fast magma ascent is critical to prevent clinopyroxene dissolution. Conversely, long-lasting magma stagnation promotes pyroxene resorption and magma differentiation. ‘Central’ eruptions occurring close to the PdF summit cone emit variably more evolved melts, which result from olivine–clinopyroxene–plagioclase differentiation at intermediate–shallow pressure (<3 kbar and in most cases <1 kbar). Deep and extensive magma mixing before injection into the crustal magma conduit system, located below the summit region, results in the apparent homogeneity of basalts erupted from the central area. As regards ‘peripheral’ eruptions, deep-seated stagnation of basaltic melts and differentiation at the mantle–crust transition zone (c. 4 kbar) produces a range of magma compositions. We demonstrate that rapid magma ascent from deep-seated reservoirs can bypass the central plumbing system. The eruptions of these magmas both in the central area and on the densely populated flanks have major consequences in terms of volcanic hazard at PdF.

transitional basalts, clinopyroxene crystallization and resorption, source heterogeneities, barometry, mantle–crust underplating

INTRODUCTION

A better knowledge of the conditions of deep magma storage systems below active volcanoes, as well as of the dynamics of magma migration towards both shallow reservoirs and the surface, is critical for understanding and forecasting volcanic activity. The physico-chemical evolution of magmas in the plumbing system of large, dominantly basaltic volcanoes occurs in a highly dynamic environment, potentially involving multiple storage zones of different sizes and depths and a plexus of connecting magmatic pathways (Eaton & Murata, 1960; Ryan, 1988; Tilling & Dvorak, 1993; Pietruszka et al., 2015; Schipper et al., 2015).

On large volcanic edifices, central and peripheral vents can be active contemporaneously and may be fed from the following: (1) a central magma reservoir that drains at variable depths from radial dykes [see Rivalta et al. (2015) for a review]; (2) long-distance sheet dykes, which may extend for kilometers during final magma ascent (Tilling & Dvorak, 1993; Ishizuka et al., 2008); (3) a deep feeding region in the mantle offset with respect to the central area (Gonzales et al., 2013; Aizawa et al., 2014; Michon et al., 2015); (4) different magma batches stored in independent reservoirs (Rittmann & Sato, 1973; Hildner et al., 2011; Zanon & Frezzotti, 2013). In any of these scenarios, contrasting magma rheological properties and the stress distribution in both basement and edifice (e.g. owing to topographic effects as well as to edifice load, regional tectonics, and the occurrence of adjacent volcanic centers) will exert a strong control on the architecture and dynamics of plumbing systems (Roman & Jaupart, 2014). An additional important parameter is the melting and magma supply rate from the mantle source to shallower magma storage regions (Vlastélic et al., 2018).

Rift zones across large volcanic edifices provide a window into their magmatic plumbing system and allow the link between central and peripheral volcanic activity to be addressed (Garcia et al., 1989). In some cases, such as at Kilauea (Hawaii), magma transfer inside rift zones occurs only at shallow levels. Small volumes of variably evolved melts can be stored close to the surface and can be then mobilized during an eruption following lateral dike injection (Ryan, 1988; Poland et al., 2014). In other cases, rift zones provide direct access to the deep storage system (e.g. Madeira, Desertas Islands and the Azores Archipelago) and testify to magma ascent from multiple storage levels located both in the crust and in the uppermost mantle (Schwarz et al., 2004; Zanon & Pimentel, 2015).

Piton de la Fournaise (PdF) comprises a central summit cone built inside the Enclos Fouqué (EF) caldera (Fig. 1) and rift zones that propagate outside the central area. The area located inside the EF caldera is the focus of the ‘central’ eruptive activity, which is the most frequent type at PdF (Villeneuve & Bachèlery, 2006; Michon et al., 2013). Outside the EF caldera, ‘peripheral’ eruptions occur along three radially oriented rift zones (Chevallier & Bachèlery, 1981; Villeneuve & Bachèlery, 2006; Michon et al., 2015): the NE rift zone (NERZ), the SE rift zone (SERZ) and the NW rift zone (NWRZ). Peripheral eruptions of PdF are infrequent (less than 3% of the historical eruptions) and poorly documented. Relatively few data exist on their magma compositions, storage conditions and ascent pathways, and the possible link with the central conduit system (Bachèlery, 1981; Bureau et al., 1998, 1999; Sigmarsson et al., 2005). A better understanding of this peripheral activity is therefore crucial to interpret seismicity and gas emissions, and also for volcanic risk assessment, because of the presence of 250 000 inhabitants in areas threatened by a potential peripheral eruption. Both the NERZ and the SERZ, which are at present almost aseismic, have been structurally related to the seaward displacement and spreading of the eastern flank of the PdF edifice. These two rift zones represent shallow pathways for lateral magma transfer from the central area, analogous to Kilauea and Etna (Acocella et al., 2003; Boivin & Bachèlery, 2009; Poland et al., 2014; Michon et al., 2015). Conversely, deep seismicity [>11 km below sea level (b.s.l.); Michon et al., 2015] is frequent below the NWRZ and potentially tracks deep magmatic pathways. The NWRZ rift possibly lies at the top of a region of deep magma storage that could promote progressive lateral magma transfer towards the central area (Michon et al., 2015). This model implies a 10–20 km offset (NW to SE) between the deep magma ponding zone and the shallow crustal plumbing system that feeds the frequently active PdF central summit area (Liuzzo et al., 2015; Boudoire et al., 2017).

Here, we integrate bulk-rock chemistry (major and trace element data, Sr–Nd isotopes), mineral chemistry, barometry and modeling for recent (<5 kyr old) lavas from both the peripheral (NWRZ) and central (EF caldera) areas of PdF to (1) compare the geochemical signatures of magmas linked to the central and peripheral activity, (2) reconstruct the conditions of magma storage and ascent, and (3) better constrain magma transfer from mantle to crustal reservoirs prior to eruptions. Because of the debated role of clinopyroxene fractionation to produce PdF magma variability (Kornprobst et al., 1979; Albarède et al., 1997; Boivin & Bachèlery, 2009; Famin et al., 2009; Brugier, 2016), we focus on a set of recent clinopyroxene-bearing basalts from both the peripheral and central areas and compare these with the volumetrically dominant olivine-bearing lavas. We argue that clinopyroxene-bearing basalts have particular significance in providing a better understanding of processes of deep magma evolution and transfer at PdF.

GENERAL SETTINGS

Geological context

La Réunion is the youngest and most active volcanic island in the Indian Ocean (Fig. 1) related to the hotspot that has been proposed to have originated the Deccan flood basalt province in western India 65 Myr ago (Courtillot et al., 1988; Duncan et al., 1989; Mahoney et al., 2002). The island is built on a Late Cretaceous to Paleocene oceanic crustal block bounded by transform faults, which shape the Mascarene Basin (Bonneville et al., 1988). The island rises 7 km above the ocean floor with the seismic Moho discontinuity being located between 10 and 13 km b.s.l. (Gallart et al., 1999; Li et al., 2003; Fontaine et al., 2015). Below this depth a jump in seismic wave velocity is possibly caused by the presence of a large, <3 km thick layer of dense material, probably related to underplating and crystallization of ascending melts (Charvis et al., 1999; Fontaine et al., 2015).

La Réunion Island is composed of two large volcanic edifices (Piton des Neiges, PdN: 3070 m a.s.l.; Piton de la Fournaise, PdF: 2632 m a.s.l.) that are made of geochemically similar magmas belonging to the transitional series (Upton & Wadsworth, 1966). PdF began its activity c. 530 kyr ago on the southwestern flank of the largest and now quiescent volcanic edifice, PdN (Gillot & Nativel, 1989). Eruptive activity of PdF mostly occurred inside the EF caldera (indicated as intracaldera or ‘central activity’). These eruptions have occurred on average once every 9 months since 1985, with an estimated bulk lava output rate of 0·15–0·38 m3 s–1 (Roult et al., 2012). Seismic hypocentres beneath the central area are mostly confined to crustal depths between 0·5 and 11 km b.s.l. (Michon et al., 2015). This crustal seismicity is related to the central magma plumbing system, composed of multiple reservoirs at variable depths (Nercessian et al., 1996; Albarède et al., 1997; Aki & Ferrazzini, 2000; Battaglia et al., 2005; Famin et al., 2009; Peltier et al., 2009; Lénat et al., 2012; Di Muro et al., 2014, 2015; Vlastélic & Pietruszka, 2016).

The EF caldera is open seaward to the east and connected by two aseismic rift zones (NERZ and SERZ), which act as pathways for shallow lateral migration of magma outside the caldera, to feed the peripheral activity (Villeneuve & Bachèlery, 2006; Michon et al., 2015). Lava output rates of the SERZ and NERZ are low (0·07–0·09 m3 s–1; Michon et al., 2015) and the chemical and mineralogical compositions of the lavas match those of magmas erupted inside the central area (Boivin & Bachèlery, 2009). A third and volcanically less active zone of peripheral activity is the NWRZ (0·03–0·06 m3 s–1 of lava emission over c. 50 kyr; Michon et al., 2015), which connects the western flank of PdF to the older PdN edifice (Fig. 1). The N120° orientation of the NWRZ has been related to regional NNE–SSW extension, which reactivates deep lithospheric faults (Michon et al., 2007, 2015; Boudoire et al., 2017). The NWRZ differs from the NERZ and SERZ by its frequent and deep seismicity (>11 km b.s.l., which is within the lithospheric mantle), and the large volume of many pyroclastic cones and associated lavas (Michon et al., 2015). As we will document below, the lavas erupted from the NWRZ zone differ in their chemistry from those emitted from both the other rift zones and the central area (Bachèlery, 1981; Lénat et al., 2012).

Magma compositions

Magmas erupted at La Réunion Island originate from partial melting (∼10%) of a slightly heterogeneous source in the upper mantle (Fisk et al., 1988; Graham et al., 1990; Staudacher et al., 1990; Hanyu et al., 2001; Fretzdorff & Haase, 2002; Putirka, 2008a; Valer et al., 2017b). The radiogenic isotope systematics indicates the occurrence of limited compositional heterogeneities in the mantle source (Bosch et al., 2008; Pietruszka et al., 2009; Di Muro et al., 2014; Valer et al., 2017b), associated with small degrees of crustal contamination (Luais, 2004; Pietruszka et al., 2009). With the exception of some old plagioclase-bearing alkali basalts, lavas at PdF are mainly transitional basalts (Upton & Wadsworth, 1966; Valer et al., 2017a), subdivided into ‘steady-state basalts’ (SSB; Albarède et al., 1997) and the ‘abnormal group basalts’ (AbG; Famin et al., 2009; Salaün et al., 2010; Lénat et al., 2012; Valer et al., 2017b).

‘Steady-state basalts’ (SSB) range from aphyric to weakly porphyritic with olivine (± clinopyroxene ± plagioclase) as the main phenocrysts; that is, minerals that formed directly from the magma in which they are hosted (Davidson et al., 2007). SSB are particularly rich in olivine (>20%) and are also known as ‘oceanites’ (Lacroix, 1923). These lavas are emitted in both the central and peripheral areas during phases characterized by high magma output rate (Albarède et al., 1997; Famin et al., 2009; Di Muro et al., 2014). Olivine crystals in these oceanites have been interpreted to be antecrysts; that is, crystals related to the magmatic system but not directly crystallized from the host magma (Davidson et al., 2007). Antecrysts can be derived from either (1) the disruption of a ‘crystal mush’ within some intracrustal reservoirs (Clocchiatti et al., 1979; Famin et al., 2009; Welsch et al., 2013; Di Muro et al., 2014) or (2) crystallized cumulate bodies located at variable depths (Albarède et al., 1997; Bureau et al., 1998).

‘Abnormal Group Basalts’ (AbG) were first documented by Albarède et al. (1997) in the roughly hundreds of thousand years old peripheral Nez de Boeuf Series (Fig. 1). These basalts have a mildly alkaline affinity, low CaO and SiO2 contents, and are enriched in both compatible and incompatible trace elements with respect to SSB. AbG are very common among the lavas emitted in the peripheral area (Lénat et al., 2012) and rarer in the central area (Boivin & Bachèlery, 2009). Occasionally, SSB- and AbG-type lavas may erupt simultaneously from distinct craters, as observed during the 1998 central eruption (SSB Kapor lavas; AbG Hudson lavas; Fig. 1). Magmas erupted in 1998 were thought to be end-member compositions whose mixing originated the magmas erupted during the 1999–2007 period (Di Muro et al., 2014). Pressures recorded by melt and fluid inclusions in olivine from SSB lavas are usually low and on average <1 kbar (Famin et al., 2009; Di Muro et al., 2016). This strongly contrasts with the AbG Hudson basalts, which carry olivine-hosted melt and fluid inclusions that record pressures up to 5 kbar (Bureau et al., 1999).

SAMPLES

For this study, we mainly sampled products erupted from the poorly studied peripheral scoria cones (i.e. outside the EF caldera and near its rim, inside the central area). We studied the following: (1) small monogenetic strombolian cones in the peripheral area (e.g. Formica Léo, Piton sous le Gîte, Piton Rampe 14, Piton de la Rivière de l’Est, Petit Cratère, Cratère Commerson), located as far as 7–8 km from the summit cone of PdF and emitting predominantly clinopyroxene-bearing basalts (Fig. 1; Supplementary Data Electronic Appendix 1; supplementary data are available for downloading at http://www.petrology.oxfordjournals.org); (2) large polygenetic cones in the peripheral area (e.g. Chisny, Demi-Piton, Haüy) that emitted olivine-bearing, aphyric to olivine-phyric basalts (Fig. 1). Dunite, wehrlite and gabbroic enclaves are common in lavas and lapilli beds emplaced during large eruptions in the peripheral area (e.g. Upton & Wadsworth, 1972; Bachèlery, 1981), but they are very rare in the central area. These enclaves represent slowly cooled cumulates in magmatic reservoirs. The age of the gabbroic cumulates is unknown, but some have interstitial melt and thus may be related to the recent magmatic history (<5 kyr old; Upton et al., 2000). Examples of dunite and wehrlite enclaves erupted from the polygenetic Chisny cone (Bureau et al., 1998; Brugier, 2016) and gabbroic clasts in the Bellecombe Ash Member (Upton et al., 2000) have been analyzed for comparison with phenocrysts and antecrysts in lavas.

Our new data are compared with the literature on the 1972–2010 lavas from the central area (Albarède et al., 1997; Vlastélic et al., 2007; Peltier, 2007; Boivin & Bachèlery, 2009; Pietruszka et al., 2009; Salaün et al., 2010; Di Muro et al., 2014, 2015). In particular, we focus on the lavas from the two largest recent central eruptions of 1998 and 2007 that show significant compositional variability and record deep magma inputs (Bureau et al., 1999; Di Muro et al., 2014).

ANALYTICAL METHODS

Major and trace elements and isotope analyses of bulk samples

Thirty-eight lava samples were crushed and finely ground in agate. Major and trace element analyses were performed at the SARM (Service d’Analyse des Roches et des Minéraux de Nancy, France; Supplementary Data Electronic Appendix 2), by inductively coupled plasma optical emission spectrometry (ICP-OES) and inductively coupled plasma mass spectrometry (ICP-MS), respectively [see Carignan et al. (2001) for a review of the protocols and of reference materials]. Relative errors are <1% (SiO2, Al2O3), <2% (MgO, FeO, CaO) and <5% (Na2O, K2O, TiO2) for major elements. Relative errors are <15% (Sc), <10% (Th, Cr) and <5% for other trace elements used in this study.

Ten analyses of Sr and Nd isotopic ratios were performed at INGV-OV (Istituto Nazionale di Geofisica e Vulcanologia–Osservatorio di Napoli, Italy). Isotopic compositions were determined on c. 0·1 g of whole-rock powders after dissolution with ultrapure acids (HF–HNO3–HCl mixtures). Sr and Nd were separated from the matrix through conventional ion-exchange procedures [standard separation scheme as described by Arienzo et al. (2013) and in references therein] and measured statically by thermal ionization mass spectrometry (TIMS; Thermo Finnigan Triton TI). During collection of the isotopic data, replicate analyses of NIST-SRM 987 (SrCO3) and La Jolla international reference standards were measured. Mean measured values for 87Sr/86Sr for the NIST-SRM 987 and 143Nd/144Nd for the La Jolla standards were 0·710219 ± 0·000018 (2σ, n = 101) and 0·511845 ± 0·000010 (2σ, n = 52), respectively. Measured 87Sr/86Sr and 143Nd/144Nd ratios were normalized for within-run isotopic fractionation to 86Sr/88Sr = 0·1194 and 146Nd/144Nd = 0·7219 and were normalized to the recommended values of 87Sr/86Sr = 0·71025 and 143Nd/144Nd = 0·511850 for the NIST-SRM 987 and La Jolla standards, respectively (Supplementary Data Electronic Appendix 2 ).

Electron microprobe analyses of mineral phases

Electron microprobe analyses of mineral phases were performed using two instruments. The first was a CAMECA SX100 electron microprobe at Camparis (Paris, France) operated with a 15 kV accelerating voltage and a 20 nA current focused beam, with counting times varying from 10 to 50 s depending on the element. Relative errors were 0·5–1·5% (SiO2, MgO), 2–4% (Al2O3, FeO, CaO), 5–15% (TiO2, K2O, Na2O) and 20–45% (NiO, MnO, Cr2O3). For olivine, the relative error on CaO was 6–10%. The second instrument was a JEOL JXA-8900RL electron microprobe (University of Göttingen, Germany) operated with a 15 kV accelerating voltage and a 15 nA current defocused beam, with 5–15 s counting times per element in minerals. Relative errors were 0·5–1·5% (SiO2, MgO, FeO, CaO, Al2O3), 1–4% (TiO2), 5–15% (Na2O, Cr2O3, NiO) and 5–35% (K2O, MnO). For olivine, the relative error on CaO was 5–10%. No systematic difference was found between the two electron microprobe datasets.

Fluid and melt inclusion barometry

Fluid inclusions were analyzed at room temperature at IPGP (Institut de Physique du Globe de Paris) using a Horiba T64000 Raman spectrometer manufactured by Jobin-Yvon with a 1800 grooves mm–1 grating, offering a high resolution (<1 cm–1) for peak identification. Fluid inclusions were excited using an Ar+ laser at 488 nm wavelength. Pressures were estimated using the CO2 density deduced from the Fermi diad split (van den Kerkhof & Olsen, 1990; Frezzotti et al., 2012) between the 1388 and 1285 cm–1 bands (Δ). We used the new densimeter of Lamadrid et al. (2016) calibrated for a Jobin-Yvon Horiba spectrometer using a 1800 grooves mm–1 grating with a 514 nm wavelength (see Supplementary Data Electronic Appendix 3 for a complete description of the procedure). The total error related to the calibration and the analytical conditions results in a maximum overestimation of CO2 densities of 0·05 g cm–3 (i.e. less than 0·7 kbar).

Additionally, we calculated the saturation pressures of volatiles dissolved in melt inclusions using the Di Muro et al. (2016) database and the H2O–CO2 solubility model of Papale et al. (2006). This model is best suited for high pressures (>5 kbar).

RESULTS

Petrography

Two main petrographic groups characterize the lavas emitted in the peripheral area. One is defined by the presence of clinopyroxene phenocrysts next to olivine. The second lacks clinopyroxene phenocrysts, but has abundant olivine phenocrysts, as typically observed in PdF lavas (Welsch et al., 2009, 2013).

The small monogenetic strombolian cones built on the NWRZ of PdF (Crater near Cratère Commerson pits, Petit Cratère, Piton sous le Gite, Piton de la Rivière de l’Est, and Formica Léo; Fig. 1) have erupted lavas with unusually abundant clinopyroxene (up to 1 mm long) that have previously been partially described in the literature (Bachèlery, 1981). These lavas, which we term here ‘clinopyroxene-bearing’ basalts, have more abundant clinopyroxene phenocrysts than olivine, and only a small amount of plagioclase (Fig. 2a). They contain skeletal olivine crystals up to 1 mm (Fig. 2b), with long dendritic overgrowths (up to 500 μm long) and sector-zoned clinopyroxene phenocrysts and microphenocrysts (Fig. 2c). Clinopyroxenes are euhedral and exhibit complex oscillatory zoning at their rims. Euhedral plagioclase microphenocrysts have only weak zoning. Rare inclusions of chromite are present in olivine and clinopyroxene. In all of these lavas, the groundmass is holocrystalline and composed of microlites of olivine, clinopyroxene, plagioclase and magnetite. Lavas erupted from different small peripheral cones show a minimal difference in their average crystal sizes and in the abundance of anhedral to subhedral olivine (Table 1). Anhedral olivine may be included in sector-zoned clinopyroxenes (Fig. 2d), suggesting that an early olivine growth was followed by cotectic olivine–clinopyroxene crystallization.

Large polygenetic cones from the peripheral NWRZ (Chisny, Haüy, Demi-Piton, Piton de Caille) erupted lavas in which olivine is the dominant mineral phase, as commonly observed in PdF lavas. They are defined here as ‘olivine-bearing’ lavas. The olivine ranges from up to 2 mm in size to microphenocrysts and microlites. Many olivine crystals are rounded and densely fractured (Fig. 2e). Clusters of polyhedral olivine crystals, like those described by Welsch et al. (2013), are rare and rounded (e.g. Fig. 2f). Olivine microphenocrysts are scattered in the groundmass. Chromite inclusions are common in olivine crystals, whereas magnetite microlites occur sparsely in the groundmass. Minor amounts of anhedral clinopyroxene microlites are confined to the groundmass, together with olivine, plagioclase and magnetite (Table 1).

Dunitic and wehrlitic enclaves are abundant only in ‘olivine-bearing’ lavas from large peripheral cones (e.g. Chisny). These ultramafic enclaves are mainly made of anhedral to subhedral olivine and clinopyroxene. Olivine crystals sometimes exhibit equilibrated 120° grain boundaries (Fig. 3a and b) and typically show patterned extinction indicating deformation bands. Chromite inclusions are common in olivine. Fragments of gabbroic cumulates with variable grain size and amounts of evolved interstitial glass are widespread in the deposits of the Bellecombe Ash Member (Upton et al., 2000). In these gabbroic clasts, olivine and clinopyroxene are generally euhedral to subhedral. Clinopyroxene exhibits complex patchy, concentric and sector-zoning patterns (Fig. 3c). The latter resemble those observed in ‘clinopyroxene-bearing’ lavas, but differ by the absence of oscillatory zoning and the occurrence of corrosion textures. Plagioclase in gabbros is smaller than olivine and clinopyroxene, and has tabular shapes and well-developed concentric and oscillatory zoning. Small gabbroic and dunitic fragments were also found in ‘clinopyroxene-bearing’ basalts (Fig. 3d).

Recent (1972–2010) lavas from the central area vary from aphyric basalts to cotectic (clinopyroxene–plagioclase ± olivine) basalts to olivine porphyritic basalts (e.g. Welsch et al., 2013). In olivine basalts, rounded clinopyroxenes with dissolution textures have been reported (Welsch et al., 2009). The 1998 lavas vary from aphyric basalts to olivine–clinopyroxene basalts (Hudson vent; small volume; Fig. 1) to rare basalts enriched in plagioclase crystals (Kapor vent; large volume; Boivin & Bachèlery, 2009). In particular, the ‘1998 clinopyroxene-bearing’ lavas of the Hudson vent, previously considered as the archetype of AbG lavas (Famin et al., 2009), display unusual textures with the largest variability in crystal sizes and shapes found in our sample set. In the Hudson samples, euhedral, anhedral and skeletal olivine crystals coexist with clinopyroxene phenocrysts (rarely sector-zoned) and plagioclase microphenocrysts (Table 1). In contrast, the 2007 lavas vary from aphyric basalts (February) to cotectic basalts (March) to olivine-rich basalts that lack clinopyroxene phenocrysts (April–May; Di Muro et al., 2014).

Mineral compositions

Olivine

‘Clinopyroxene-bearing’ basalts from peripheral eruptions share a similar composition of equilibrium olivine (Fig. 4a). Olivine core compositions are Fo83·5–81·5, whereas rims and dendrites are iron-rich (<Fo81·5; Fig. 4a). In ‘olivine-bearing’ lavas from peripheral cones, the olivine composition is polymodal with higher modes of MgO content and a wider range compared with ‘clinopyroxene-bearing’ basalts (Fig. 4b;Brugier, 2016). In cognate cumulate enclaves (Brugier, 2016), the average MgO content of olivine decreases from dunites to wehrlites to gabbros (Fig. 4c). The olivine composition is bimodal in dunites (Fo87·5 and Fo84). Wehrlites lack MgO-rich olivine crystals, but share a common composition of olivine with dunites (Fo84). Gabbroic clasts from the Bellecombe Ash Member contain MgO-poor olivine crystals (Fo<82) with a main mode at Fo78, consistent with previous studies (Upton et al., 2000). The olivine composition in 1977–2010 lavas from the central area is bimodal (Fig. 4d) and is best represented by the products of the 2007 eruptions. The main and MgO-richest mode centered at Fo84·5–84·0 is best represented by phenocrysts in olivine-rich lavas from the large-volume April 2007 eruption (Fig. 4e). The second mode is centered at Fo81·5 as observed in the cotectic basalts from the small-volume March 2007 eruption (Fig. 4e;Di Muro et al., 2014). Olivine crystals from ‘1998 clinopyroxene-bearing’ lavas from the Hudson vent show a wide compositional range (centered at Fo86), with unusually high MgO contents (up to Fo88·2; Fig. 4f), not in equilibrium with the host-rock. MgO-rich olivine crystals (Fo>84·5) found in lavas from central eruptions are neither in equilibrium with the host groundmass and bulk-rocks, nor with the most magnesian glasses found in pyroclasts from central eruptions (MgO: 8·6 wt % in April 2007 and 8·7 wt % in December 2008; Villemant et al., 2009; Di Muro et al., 2015).

Fig. 4

Distribution of forsterite (Fo) content (%) in olivine phenocrysts and microphenocrysts from lavas and enclaves of Piton de la Fournaise. (a) ‘Clinopyroxene-bearing’ basalts (Petit Cratère, Formica Léo) from peripheral eruptions contain olivine crystals with cores of a unimodal forsterite composition (main mode at Fo83 and a tail towards lower Fo). (b) ‘Olivine-bearing’ basalts (Chisny, Haüy; Brugier, 2016; this study) and olivine-rich basalts (Piton de Caille; Bureau et al., 1998) emitted in the peripheral area contain olivine crystals with a broad polymodal forsterite content distribution (up to Fo88·8) and main compositional modes in the Fo83·5–86·5 range. (c) Bimodal olivine composition (Fo84 and Fo87·5) is observed in dunites (Brugier, 2016). The Fo content of the main mode decreases from dunites to wehrlites (Fo84; Brugier, 2016), to gabbros (Fo78; this study). (d) Bimodal distribution of olivine composition (modes at Fo84–84·5 and Fo81·5) in typical lavas emitted inside the central area during the 1977–2010 central activity. (e) Distinct distribution and modes of olivine composition in March 2007 aphyric lavas and April 2007 aphyric to olivine-rich lavas. (f) Olivine composition in March 1998 lavas of the Kapor Crater (SSB) and of the Hudson Crater (AbG). Our data show that olivine populations can also be discriminated on the basis of their concentrations of Ca, which diffuses more slowly than Fe and Mg (Coogan et al., 2005). Two trends are recognized here (Fig. 5a and b) confirming previous findings by Di Muro et al. (2015). In trend 1, found in ‘2007 olivine-bearing’ lavas from the central area, CaO increases with decreasing Fo. In trend 2, CaO exhibits little variation over a range of Fo, as shown by the ‘1998 clinopyroxene-bearing’ lavas at the Hudson vent. The composition of olivine in ‘clinopyroxene-bearing’ lavas from peripheral eruptions lies on (or between) these two trends (Fig. 5a). In contrast, olivine from ‘olivine-bearing’ lavas in the peripheral area shows a wide range in CaO contents at a given Fo (Fig. 5b). The CaO content progressively increases from core to rim, whereas Fo decreases. High CaO contents (up to 0·45 wt %) are measured mostly in olivine ≈Fo84. Conversely, low CaO contents (<0·1 wt %) are found in the cores of many olivine crystals with a large compositional range (Fo82–86). MgO-rich olivine crystals in dunites and wehrlites present a compositional spectrum similar to that observed in ‘olivine-bearing’ lavas from peripheral eruptions (Fig. 5c). These anomalous low CaO contents, however, could result from a process of sub-solidus diffusive re-equilibration (Brugier, 2016). Conversely, in Bellecombe gabbros, olivine composition falls on Trend 2; that is, like those found in ‘clinopyroxene-bearing’ lavas from peripheral eruptions.

Fig. 5

CaO content (wt %) relative to Fo content (%) in olivine crystals from (a) ‘clinopyroxene-bearing’ lavas and (b) ‘olivine-bearing’ lavas from both peripheral and central areas, and (c) cumulates. Two trends are observed in olivine of lavas erupted from the central area. Trend 1 (Fo decrease and CaO enrichment) is best represented by olivine in the March 1998 (Kapor), March and April 2007 lavas (Boivin & Bachèlery, 2009; Villemant et al., 2009; Di Muro et al., 2014) labeled 1998 (K), 2007 (M) and 2007 (A), respectively. Trend 2 (Fo decrease and almost constant CaO content) is represented by olivine in March 1998 (Hudson) lavas labeled 1998 (H). Olivine crystals in ‘clinopyroxene-bearing’ lavas from the peripheral area (PC, FL) fall on these trends. Scattered CaO contents occur in olivine from ‘olivine-bearing’ lavas emitted in the peripheral area (CHI, HA; Brugier, 2016; this study). Red shaded box highlights the expected range of forsterite contents of olivine in equilibrium with ‘olivine-bearing’ bulk-rock compositions (CHI, HA). Olivine in dunites and wehrlites spans a broad CaO range (Brugier, 2016). Most olivine crystals from the Bellecombe olivine–clinopyroxene gabbros fall on the low-Ca Trend 2.

Pyroxene

‘Clinopyroxene-bearing’ basalts that erupted in the peripheral area (Table 2) contain mainly augite phenocrysts (XWo = 0·40 ± 0·03; International Mineralogical Association nomenclature, Morimoto, 1988). Diopside (XWo = 0·45 ± 0·02) with augite rims is rarely observed (e.g. Formica Léo). Only iron-rich augite microlites occur in the groundmass of ‘olivine-bearing’ lavas emitted in the peripheral area. Diopside is more common in gabbroic cumulates (XWo = 0·45 ± 0·01) and the most calcic clinopyroxenes occur in dunitic and wehrlitic enclaves (XWo = 0·47 ± 0·01). In basalts erupted in the central area, augites and Mg-augites have been reported (Albarède et al., 1997; Boivin & Bachèlery, 2009; Di Muro et al., 2015; Peltier, 2007) but diopside is scarce (Clocchiatti et al., 1979; Peltier, 2007).

Sector-zoning in clinopyroxenes can potentially affect their classification and their use for barometric purposes. Two clinopyroxene compositions are found in ‘clinopyroxene-bearing’ basalts from peripheral eruptions and in some Bellecombe gabbros, corresponding to distinct sectors of the crystals (Fig. 6a). Bright zones in back-scattered electron (BSE) images are enriched in Ti and Al, whereas dark zones are enriched in Mg and Si (Fig. 6a;Table 2). Meanwhile, ratios such as Mg/Fe and Ti/Al do not significantly differ in growth zones (Table 2; Supplementary Data Electronic Appendix 2) and may thus be reliable to compare the clinopyroxene composition in lavas from various eruptive vents (Fig. 6b). Using a Kd = 0·27 for Fe–Mg partitioning between melt and clinopyroxene (Putirka, 2008b; Brugier, 2016), we calculated the average Mg-numbers of clinopyroxene crystals in equilibrium with their host lavas, for both peripheral and central areas. The calculated (88·1–82·1) and measured (85·7–80·5) Mg-numbers (×100) are in good agreement (Supplementary Data Electronic Appendix 4). The only exceptions are the microlites in the groundmass of ‘olivine-bearing’ lavas from peripheral eruptions and the microphenocrysts in 1998 ‘clinopyroxene-bearing’ lavas, which are too iron-rich and in equilibrium only with more evolved (MgO <5 wt %) melts (Fig. 6b;Supplementary Data Electronic Appendix 4). The highest Mg-numbers (94–96) and the lowest Ti/Al ratios (down to 0·11) are in the clinopyroxene of dunites (Mg-numbers 87–94; Ti/Al 0·11–0·22). The absence of Al enrichment in low Ti/Al clinopyroxenes from dunites and wehrlites is consistent with previous findings on magnesian clinopyroxene at PdF (Fisk et al., 1988; Fretzdorff & Haase, 2002). Clinopyroxene in gabbroic cumulates from the Bellecombe deposit has a low Mg-number (78–90) and its Ti/Al (0·18–0·32) overlaps the upper range found in clinopyroxene in lavas from both the central and peripheral areas (for the same Mg-number; Table 2).

Feldspars

Plagioclase in ‘clinopyroxene-bearing’ lavas from peripheral centres is mostly not zoned, with a composition ranging from An72·1Ab27·4Or0·5 to An53·5Ab44·2Or2·3. Plagioclase (An68·3Ab30·3Or1·4 and An45·7Ab51·7Or2·6) is also present in the matrices of ‘olivine-bearing’ lavas erupted from the peripheral area. However, An contents are lower than those in ‘clinopyroxene-bearing’ lavas and consistent with crystallization from more alkaline melts. Plagioclase in Bellecombe gabbros records the highest anorthite content measured in this study (An84·8Ab14·8Or0·4). There, rare alkali feldspars up to An3·1Ab62·5Or34·4 are also observed. Plagioclase in lavas from the central area ranges from An79·0Ab20·2Or0·8 to An60·5Ab38·5Or1·0 and complex zoning is observed in both phenocrysts and microlites (Boivin & Bachèlery, 2009; Di Muro et al., 2015). In ‘1998 clinopyroxene-bearing’ lavas, plagioclase is sodic, ranging from An67·4Ab31·7Or0·9 to An57·7Ab40·8Or1·5 and is generally not zoned.

Barometry

Pyroxene barometry

The clinopyroxene-based barometry is sensitive to the jadeite component (NaAlSi2O6), which increases with pressure, but is also influenced by temperature, water content and sector-zoning (Fig. 6a). As expected, data resulting from sector-zoned clinopyroxene crystals gave large pressure ranges for different sectors of the same crystal. We found that the clinopyroxene–melt equilibrium barometer [equation (30), Putirka et al., 2003] returns systematically higher and more variable pressures (ΔP ∼2 kbar) for different growth zones compared with the clinopyroxene-only barometer [ΔP <1 kbar; equation (32b), Putirka, 2008b]. For this reason, we use the clinopyroxene-only barometer of Putirka (2008b), which allows integration of a larger dataset (Fig. 7), and reduces the uncertainty related to the barometer calibration (Putirka, 2008b). Crystallization pressures for several crystals in each sample, from both the peripheral and central areas (Fig. 7), are calculated. An uncertainty (1σ) of 2·6 kbar is reported from experimental calibrations, but for a large and consistent analytical dataset for many equilibrium clinopyroxene–melt pairs, this uncertainty is considerably reduced by averaging calculated pressures (Putirka, 2017). We thus report averaged pressure values with a 1σ uncertainty. Following Hammer et al. (2016), we assume that sectors low in Na and Al (dark sectors; Fig. 2b) provide minimum pressure estimates for sector-zoned pyroxenes (Fig. 7).

Fig. 7

Clinopyroxene crystallization pressures in Piton de la Fournaise magmas. (a, d) Clinopyroxene–melt geothermobarometry [equation (30), Putirka et al., 2003] based on iterative determination of pressure and temperature. Only clinopyroxene cores in equilibrium with the bulk-rocks (Kd = 0·27 ± 0·03) are reported here (Putirka, 2008b). Clinopyroxene microlites from ‘olivine-bearing basalts’ emitted in the peripheral area (Chisny, Haüy) and in 1998 ‘clinopyroxene-bearing’ lavas emitted at the Hudson vent in the central area are in disequilibrium with the bulk-rock (equilibrium with <5 wt % MgO melts). (b, c, e) Pressure distribution from clinopyroxene-only geothermobarometry [equation (32b), Putirka, 2008b] was calculated for hydrous (H2O = 1 wt %; average in Piton de la Fournaise melts; Di Muro et al., 2016) melts with equation (32c). Consistent and similar pressure ranges are obtained with equation (32a) calibrated for dry melts. Temperature is estimated from bulk-rock compositions based on the MgO thermometer developed by Helz & Thornber (1987). For gabbroic cumulates, temperature was fixed at 1200°C in accordance with the average temperature of Piton de la Fournaise magmas (Pichavant et al., 2016). A higher temperature (1250°C) was computed for dunites and wehrlites corresponding to the average temperature of clinopyroxene appearance (see Modeling section). Average pressures (and 1σ variations on the average) are reported for each distribution.

Open in new tabDownload slide

In clinopyroxene phenocrysts from ‘clinopyroxene-bearing’ lavas from peripheral eruptions, dark sectors provided a minimum average pressure of 3·1 ± 0·6 kbar. The highest pressures are recorded in clinopyroxene from dunite–wehrlite enclaves erupted as lithic fragments from the polygenetic Chisny cone, with an average of 5·6 ± 0·8 kbar. A lower average pressure (2·8 ± 0·6 kbar) is documented from crystals in Bellecombe gabbros. In 1977–2010 lavas from the central area, Na contents are close to those found in clinopyroxene from the Bellecombe gabbros (Fig. 6a;Table 2). There, the clinopyroxene-only hydrous barometer provides a main mode at 2·6 ± 1·1 kbar. Clinopyroxene compositions in 1998 ‘clinopyroxene-bearing’ lavas returned an average pressure of 3·6 ± 0·9 kbar, in agreement with H2O–CO2 saturation pressures estimated from melt and fluid inclusions in MgO-rich olivine (Bureau et al., 1999). Similar relative pressure indicators were found when considering the correlation between clinopyroxene Mg-number and Ti/Al ratio (Fig. 6b). For a given Mg-number, and at constant oxygen fugacity, Ti content and thus Ti/Al decrease with increasing pressure (Adam & Green, 1994; Pichavant et al., 2016), whereas isobaric melt evolution (traced by Mg-number) can produce variable Ti/Al ratios depending on the other crystallizing phases (Boivin & Bachèlery, 2009; Di Muro et al., 2015). Average Ti/Al ratios at constant Mg-number increase (mostly related to Ti variations in our case) from clinopyroxene crystals in ‘clinopyroxene-bearing’ lavas of peripheral eruptions to those in Bellecombe gabbros and in lavas emitted from the central area (Fig. 6b).

In summary, our results suggest that clinopyroxene crystallization occurred over a large pressure range, but always <9 kbar and mostly <6 kbar. Clinopyroxene crystallization pressures partially overlap in lavas from the central and peripheral areas, but the main modes of 3–6 kbar in peripheral basalts and ultramafic enclaves (dunites and wehrlites) are systematically higher than those for the lavas from the central area and in the Bellecombe gabbros. It is known that clinopyroxene barometry needs additional experiments to be refined; however, we underline that both fluid inclusion data and AlphaMELTS modelling corroborate our clinopyroxene-derived pressures (see below).

Fluid inclusions

Primary fluid inclusions in crystals are rarely observed in ‘clinopyroxene-bearing’ lavas from peripheral eruptions (Fig. 8a and b). In this group of lavas, trails of secondary fluid inclusions (Bodnar, 2003) are found only in rare subhedral olivine antecrysts (Fig. 8c). In olivine crystals from ‘olivine-bearing’ lavas from peripheral eruptions, rare primary fluid inclusions are present, but trails of secondary fluid inclusions are frequent. Conversely, crystals in wehrlites contain both abundant primary and secondary fluid inclusions (Fig. 8d). In general, the CO2 density in primary fluid inclusions in olivine (0·28–0·53 g cm–3) is higher than that in clinopyroxene (0·10–0·41 g cm–3). We suspect that this difference reflects, at least in part, advanced re-equilibration of fluid inclusions in clinopyroxene compared with those in olivine. This process might be favored by the tendency of clinopyroxene to deform and to crack causing poorer sealing capability compared with olivine.

Fig. 8

Transmitted light photomicrographs of fluid inclusions (Fl) in crystals from Piton de la Fournaise lavas. (a) Primary fluid inclusion in an olivine dendrite from a ‘clinopyroxene-bearing’ lava from the peripheral area (e.g. Petit Cratère). (b) Primary fluid inclusions in a clinopyroxene rim from a ‘clinopyroxene-bearing’ lava from the peripheral area (Formica Léo). (c) Trail of secondary fluid inclusions in an Fo84 olivine antecryst from a ‘clinopyroxene-bearing’ lava from the peripheral area (Formica Léo). (d) Abundant primary and secondary fluid inclusions in anhedral olivine within wehrlitic enclaves from Chisny in the peripheral area. (e) Raman spectra of the Fermi dyad of CO2 in fluid inclusions exhibit well measurable shifts from low density (e.g. secondary fluid inclusion in olivine from wehrlite) to high density (e.g. secondary fluid inclusion in subhedral olivine antecryst).

Open in new tabDownload slide

In crystals from ‘clinopyroxene-bearing’ lavas from peripheral eruptions, CO2 densities in fluid inclusions range from 0·18 to 0·58 g cm–3 (equivalent to 0·7–2·9 kbar pressure). Higher-pressure fluid inclusions (up to 4·0 kbar) were observed in rare Fo84 subhedral olivine antecrysts (Fig. 4a; CO2 density 0·68 g cm–3). In contrast, micro-Raman data on fluid inclusions in olivine phenocrysts in ‘olivine-bearing’ lavas from peripheral eruptions display the highest pressures (mostly 1·7–4·2 kbar; Table 3). Our new results are consistent with the pressure range (3·2–5·7 kbar) previously recorded in olivine crystals from oceanites of the peripheral Piton de Caille eruption (Bureau et al., 1998). Fluid inclusions from crystals in dunitic and wehrlitic enclaves record a large range of densities from 0·31 to 0·53 g cm–3 (1·3–2·5 kbar) for olivine and from 0·11 to 0·45 g cm–3 for clinopyroxene (0·4–2·0 kbar). These values are consistent with thermo-barometric results obtained by Bureau et al. (1998) on Chisny dunites (0·9–4·8 kbar). A review of published data (recalculated from Famin et al., 2009) shows that fluid inclusions in olivine crystal found in lavas from the central area have very low densities, consistent with trapping and/or re-equilibration at a pressure range lower than 0·9 kbar, and in most cases <0·7 kbar. This range is consistent with the low CO2–H2O saturation pressures recorded by melt inclusions hosted in olivine from lavas emitted from the central area (Table 4; Di Muro et al., 2016). The 1998 ‘clinopyroxene-bearing’ lavas at the Hudson vent represent a rare exception, featuring fluid inclusions with high CO2 density in olivine crystals in lavas from the central area. There, fluid inclusions in MgO-rich olivine crystals suggest that magma crystallized up to a maximum pressure of 4·4 kbar (Table 4; Bureau et al., 1999).

Bulk-rocks

Lavas from both peripheral and central areas are transitional basalts (Fig. 9a), with slight tholeiitic or alkaline affinities, whereas only rare peripheral eruptions produced basalts with an alkaline affinity. Our data partly contradict the conclusions drawn by Salaün et al. (2010) and Lénat et al. (2012), who proposed that all lavas from the peripheral area display an alkaline signature.

Peripheral area

‘Clinopyroxene-bearing’ basalts (n = 6) from peripheral eruptions are compositionally variable (Figs 9–11) and span the full range from transitional basalts with a tholeiitic affinity [sample Petit Cratère (PC); MgO = 7·5 wt %, K2O = 0·58 wt %] to transitional basalts with an alkaline affinity [sample Cratère Commerson (CC); MgO = 9·3 wt %, K2O = 0·81 wt %]. However, the majority of these basalts have a tholeiitic affinity (Fig. 9a) with a CaO/Al2O3 ratio greater than 0·75 (Fig. 9), no Eu depletion, low Th contents and high Sc, middle rare earth element (MREE) and heavy REE (HREE) contents (Figs 10 and 11a). The highest 143Nd/144Nd and the lowest 87Sr/86Sr compositions are observed in these basalts (Fig. 11b and c).
