‘Olivine-bearing’ basalts (n = 30) from the peripheral area are also compositionally variable (Figs 9–11). For instance, at Chisny, early stage lavas (first phases of activity) are less alkaline and more calcic (sample CHI; K2O <0·8 wt % and CaO/Al2O3 = 0·76 ± 0·04) than late-stage lavas (last phases of activity: sample CHI*; K2O >0·9 wt % and CaO/Al2O3 = 0·68 ± 0·01). ‘Olivine-bearing’ basalts from the peripheral area have on average higher alkali contents (K2O from 0·70 to >1 wt %), lower SiO2 contents and CaO/Al2O3 ratios down to 0·66 for a given MgO, compared with the ‘clinopyroxene-bearing’ basalts from the peripheral area (Fig. 9). They are also characterized by high Th contents and low Sc, MREE and HREE with respect to ‘clinopyroxene-bearing’ basalts and do not show Eu depletion (Figs 10 and 11a). They are marked by the lowest 143Nd/144Nd and the highest 87Sr/86Sr found in PdF subaerial lavas (Fig. 11b and c).

We note that some of the ‘clinopyroxene-bearing’ and many of the ‘olivine-bearing’ lavas from peripheral eruptions, marked by low CaO/Al2O3 ratios [e.g. samples from Cratère Commerson (CC) and Chisny (CHI*); Fig. 9], also display high Th and low Sc (Fig. 10), MREE and HREE contents (Fig. 11). However, lavas with high CaO/Al2O3 ratios [e.g. samples from Formica Léo (FL) and Demi-Piton(DP*) in Figs 10 and 11] do not systematically display low Th and high MREE and HREE contents. Similarly, the Sr and Nd isotope ratios do not correlate with CaO/Al2O3. For example, the early and late-stage lavas of Chisny (CHI and CHI* samples, respectively) are isotopically similar, despite differences in major and trace element abundances and ratios (Figs 8–11b). Sr and Nd isotopes are roughly anti-correlated, but do not correlate significantly with elemental ratios of LREE/HREE, as previously observed by Albarède et al. (1997). We only observe a weak positive correlation between 87Sr/86Sr and ratios of variably incompatible elements (i.e. Th/Yb; Fig. 11c) as previously observed (Pietruszka et al., 2009; Di Muro et al., 2014).

Central area

The major and trace element compositions, as well as Sr–Nd isotopes, of the 1972–2010 lavas from central eruptions overlap partly with values for ‘clinopyroxene-bearing’ and ‘olivine-bearing’ basalts from peripheral eruptions (Figs 9–11). However, the 1972–2010 lavas display a slight Eu depletion (Eu/Eu* down to 0·96; Fig. 10b) when compared with basalts from the peripheral area (Eu/Eu* = 1·04 ± 0·01). In particular, the 1998 ‘clinopyroxene-bearing’ lavas from the Hudson vent have CaO/Al2O3 ratios, Th and REE contents, and isotopic compositions similar to those of some ‘olivine-bearing’ lavas from peripheral eruptions (e.g. CHI*; Boivin & Bachèlery, 2009; Famin et al., 2009; Villemant et al., 2009; Salaün et al., 2010) but are marked by slightly stronger Eu depletion (Eu/Eu* = 0·98; Fig. 10b). In contrast, the 2007 ‘olivine-bearing’ lavas erupted on 5 April have a composition (MgO = 8·6 wt % and K2O = 0·63 wt % in glass) similar to those of some ‘clinopyroxene-bearing’ lavas from the peripheral area with respect to major and trace elements as well as Sr–Nd isotopes.

Modeling of magma evolution

To constrain the polybaric evolution of PdF magmas we used the AlphaMELTS code (e.g. Ghiorso & Sack, 1995; Ghiorso et al., 2001; Asimow et al., 2003). This thermodynamic model takes into account the role of temperature, pressure, water content and redox state in the evolution of basaltic melts. For the calculations, we used the composition of the primary melt (Supplementary Data Electronic Appendix 5) in equilibrium with the MgO-richest olivine crystals found at PdF (Fo90·4) reported by Fretzdorff & Haase (2002). Among several possible compositions of primary melts estimated for La Réunion magmas (Ludden, 1978; Sobolev & Nikogosian, 1994; Villemant et al., 2009), this is the most primitive melt (MgO = 17·2 wt %) and thus the most likely to represent the parental melt composition for deep magmatic crystallization (9 kbar; Fretzdorff & Haase, 2002). We fix the initial temperature at 1350°C using the MgO thermometer of Helz & Thornber (1987), which has been shown to be appropriate for PdF magmas (Di Muro et al., 2016). This value is close to the 1330°C estimate of Fretzdorff & Haase (2002).

In a first set of MELT models (Simulation 1; Supplementary Data Electronic Appendix 5), we simulated isobaric equilibrium crystallization at four pressures (9, 6, 4 and 3 kbar) spanning the range constrained by clinopyroxene and fluid inclusion barometry (Fig. 12a). Model 1 (9 kbar) corresponds to the deepest potential storage zone suggested by Albarède et al. (1997) and Fretzdorff & Haase (2002) and to the highest pressure estimated by pyroxene barometry (Supplementary Data Electronic Appendix 5). Model 2 (6 kbar) corresponds to the highest pressure recorded by fluid inclusions in crystals from lavas from the peripheral area (Table 4). Model 3 (4 kbar) is close to the pressure recorded by the majority of fluid inclusions and is consistent with the depth range of the underplating layer identified by geophysical measurements (Charvis et al., 1999; Fontaine et al., 2015). Finally, Model 4 (3 kbar) accounts for pressures recorded in ‘clinopyroxene-bearing’ lavas from the peripheral area. An initial oxygen fugacity of NNO – 0·5 (where NNO is nickel–nickel oxide buffer) was selected in accordance with the recent review of Pichavant et al. (2016). Simulations were also run changing the initial dissolved water content from (1) dry conditions to (2) intermediate water contents (0·8 wt %), according to the average concentrations measured in most melt inclusions at PdF (Di Muro et al., 2016) and (3) high water contents (1·3 wt %) as estimated by Di Muro et al. (2014) for the 5 April 2007 deep magma input into the central area. The range of water concentration is slightly higher than that estimated by Putirka (2008a) for the primary magmas of La Réunion (H2O = 0·52 wt %). However, Putirka’s calculations were made for hot (1573°C) asthenospheric melts produced by 13·5% mantle partial melting, and did not take into account potential water enrichment of melts by crystallization in the pressure range between 40 and 10 kbar. Five runs were performed at 9 kbar to assess the influence of water content and oxidation state on phase equilibria (Fig. 12a;Supplementary Data Electronic Appendix 5, Simulation 1). In all runs, the first liquidus phase to form is olivine, followed by clinopyroxene. At 9 kbar, in dry basalts, Fo89 olivine appears at 1350°C and clinopyroxene (augite) at 1330°C. Decreasing pressure to 3 kbar delays pyroxene appearance and expands significantly the field of olivine stability. At 3 kbar, cotectic Fo84 olivine and clinopyroxene (augite) form at 1140°C. Our modeling predicts that the molar Ti/Al ratio in clinopyroxenes increases from 0·14 to 0·25 with decreasing pressure. An increasing amount of dissolved water (up to 1·3 wt %) further delays clinopyroxene crystallization by about 90°C and thus may play an important role. Changes in oxidation state have only a minor effect and change only slightly the olivine composition (Supplementary Data Electronic Appendix 5). Regardless of the assumed pressure, early olivine is very magnesian (Fo91–89). Such MgO-rich olivine crystals, however, are only rarely found in PdF lavas (Di Muro et al., 2016). Small MgO-rich olivine grains in AbG Hudson lavas from the central area (Bureau et al., 1999) and in lavas from the Haüy peripheral vent (Fig. 5b) show a composition up to Fo88 but are not in equilibrium with their host (bulk-rocks and matrix glasses).

Fig. 12

AlphaMELTS modeling of Piton de la Fournaise magma evolution as a function of (a) oxygen fugacity, water content and pressure. Primary melt (black star) estimated by Fretzdorff & Haase (2002) for La Réunion Island is based on equilibrium with the most MgO-rich olivine found in submarine lavas (Fo90·4). Temperature of clinopyroxene first appareance and modeled cotectic olivine composition are indicated in italics for each simulation. (b) CaO/Al2O3 and (c) Al2O3 evolution paths fitting the composition of ‘clinopyroxene-bearing’ lavas (3–4 kbar) and ‘olivine-bearing’ lavas (6 kbar) emitted in the peripheral area are reproduced starting from a primitive melt (white star). Primitive melt composition results from 19 wt % olivine fractionation from the primary melt of Fretzdorff & Haase (2002). The composition of this primitive melt (10·3 wt % MgO; 1·0 wt % H2O; NNO – 0·5) is consistent with those of the most magnesian melt inclusions found in olivines (Bureau et al., 1998; Di Muro et al., 2016). Olivine–clinopyroxene crystallization (>3 kbar) fits with the composition of lavas emitted in the peripheral area. Differentiation at 3 kbar can reproduce the evolved glass composition found in the Bellecombe gabbros (Upton et al., 2000). The addition of olivine antecrysts controls part of the variability of bulk-rock compositions. MgO-rich olivine antecrysts (Fo84 as modeled at 4 kbar, consistent with the pressure recorded by fluid inclusions) are indeed observed in Formica Léo lavas and part of the geochemical variability of lavas from peripheral vents can be explained by addition of <10% of olivine antecrysts (this study).

Open in new tabDownload slide

To explore the potential effect of deep magma storage and early olivine fractionation, we performed a second set of runs starting with a lower MgO content for the parental magma (Simulation 2; Supplementary Data Electronic Appendix 5). In these runs, we fixed the starting melt composition (MgO = 10·3 wt %; H2O = 1·0 wt %; Fig. 12b) to that of a primitive melt that had already fractionated 19 wt % of MgO-rich olivine at 9 kbar. This starting composition is close to that of the most primitive melt inclusions found in olivine (Bureau et al., 1998; Di Muro et al., 2016). At 6 kbar (Fig. 12b and c), cooling and crystallization of primary magma produces olivine Fo87–85 similar to that of the MgO-richest olivine found in ‘olivine-bearing’ lavas from peripheral eruptions and dunites. In this scenario, we find that the ‘early’ CaO/Al2O3 decrease at high MgO recorded by some ‘olivine-bearing’ lavas from peripheral eruptions (e.g. samples from Chisny, CHI* in Fig. 12b and c) can be reproduced only by predominant crystallization of pyroxene at 6 kbar and temperatures lower than 1270°C. This process drives the initial melt composition after fractionation of 4 wt % olivine and 12 wt % clinopyroxene close to that of the associated mafic glasses (c. 8 wt % MgO for Chisny; Fig. 12b and c). At 4 kbar, the simulation reproduces cotectic pyroxene together with an olivine composition (Fo84) like that observed in the natural ‘clinopyroxene-bearing’ lavas from both the peripheral and central areas of PdF. Computed magma compositions are close to the composition of ‘clinopyroxene-bearing’ lavas from the peripheral area. Our modeling also shows that low-MgO olivine (<Fo84) (i.e. the dominant type of olivine erupted in the central area of PdF) typically forms at pressures lower than 3 kbar from evolved melts (MgO <6·3 wt %). Plagioclase is never stable in mafic melts (MgO >5 wt %) in the pressure range 3–9 kbar at temperatures between 1140 and 1350°C and water contents between 0·8 and 1·3 wt %.

DISCUSSION

Polybaric magma evolution at Piton de la Fournaise

Barometric data allow us to formulate a refined model of the magma plumbing system at PdF (see Table 4 and Fig. 13a for a summary). Results of fluid inclusion studies and pyroxene barometry closely agree for lavas from peripheral vents whose crystal shapes indicate fast crystal growth (Fig. 1). Relatively to these products, the majority of primary fluid inclusions in olivine phenocrysts record a maximum pressure of 2·9 ± 0·7 kbar, consistent with the average pressure estimated by clinopyroxene barometry (3·1 ± 0·6 kbar; Fig. 7b). Higher pressure values (up to 4·0 ± 0·7 kbar) are recorded only by trails of secondary fluid inclusions in MgO-rich olivine antecrysts (Table 4). In lavas from the central area, previous studies have found that the majority of melt and fluid inclusions trapped in olivine Fo80–85 indicate pressures lower than 0·9 kbar (Bureau et al., 1998, 1999; Famin et al., 2009; Di Muro et al., 2014, 2016), and in most cases below 0·7 kbar (Famin et al., 2009). The pressures estimated using fluid and melt inclusion barometry are always much lower than the values derived from clinopyroxene geothermobarometry (2·7 ± 1·1 kbar; Fig. 7e). The observed discrepancy may result from a combination of several processes such as the following: (1) an overestimation of pressures from the clinopyroxene-based barometry of Putirka (2008b) owing to kinetic effects during crystal growth on Mg–Fe partitioning (Mollo et al., 2010); (2) the incorporation of olivine antecrysts (Salaün et al., 2010) from shallow cumulate bodies, similar to those encountered by the Grand Brulé drillcore below the eastern flank of the volcano (<2 kbar; Rancon et al., 1989); (3) late crystallization of low-MgO olivine (Fo<84) during low-pressure magma evolution (Di Muro et al., 2015, 2016) after the deep crystallization of MgO-rich olivine (Fo>84) and clinopyroxene; (4) late-stage re-equilibration of inclusions and diffusive loss of volatiles during magma storage in the shallow part of the central plumbing system (Wanamaker et al., 1990; Famin et al., 2009). Option (1) is not realistic in our case as we found a good agreement between clinopyroxene and fluid inclusion barometry for the peripheral samples. Hence, this feature validates the pressure range computed for samples from the central area. A significant effect of antecryst incorporation (Option 2) can be also discarded as the majority of olivine crystals in lavas from the central area are phenocrysts in equilibrium with their host (Fig. 4). Late olivine crystallization (Option 3) at shallow levels produces low-MgO olivine (Fo81·5) that is indeed found in many evolved lavas from the central area. There, MgO-richest olivines (Fo84–88), resulting from earlier and deeper magma differentiation, are poorly represented, possibly because of diffusive re-equilibration during longer storage in the central conduit (Option 4). Consequently, we suggest that the clinopyroxene-only barometry tracks the early and deep stages of high-pressure evolution of these magmas from the central area, whereas this information is not preserved in fluid inclusions owing to re-equilibration and later long-term magma ponding at a shallower level. Similar differences between fluid inclusion and clinopyroxene barometries have been also reported for lavas from the Canary Islands and Madeira, and have been attributed to the resetting of partially decrepitated inclusions during storage at shallow depth (Hansteen et al., 1998; Schwarz et al., 2004).

Fig. 13

Compilation of the most notable petrological and geochemical markers in Piton de la Fournaise melts that are discussed in this study. (a) Comparison between clinopyroxene and fluid inclusion barometry. Pressure ranges are provided for each sample taking into account for fluid inclusions the natural variability and the maximum analytical error (σ = 0·7 kbar) and for clinopyroxene the 1σ variation on the average. Variations in (b) major elements (MgO vs CaO/Al2O3) and (c) trace elements (Th/Yb vs CaO/Al2O3) in Piton de la Fournaise lavas from both central and peripheral areas. The geochemical variability of Piton de la Fournaise lavas has been attributed to the following: (1) the melting of small-scale, slight heterogeneities in the mantle plume source to variable degrees (Albarède & Tamagnan, 1988; Bosch et al., 2008; Pietruszka et al., 2009; Di Muro et al., 2014; Vlastélic et al., 2018); (2) evolution of magnesian parental melt controlled by clinopyroxene fractionation (Albarède et al., 1997; Boivin & Bachèlery, 2009; Famin et al., 2009; Salaün et al., 2010); (3) olivine cannibalism by evolved magmas (Salaün et al., 2010); or (4) contamination or mixing of magnesian melts with differentiated melts (Salaün et al., 2010) or with low-degree melts of wehrlite cumulates (this study; Pietruszka et al., 2009). These hypotheses are numbered in the figure and are discussed further in the text.

Open in new tabDownload slide

High pressures estimated based on fluid and melt inclusion barometry are ubiquitous in lavas emitted in the peripheral area. Bureau et al. (1998) reported the highest pressures in melt inclusions (up to 2·9 kbar) and fluid inclusions (up to 5·7 kbar) in MgO-rich (Fo87–85) olivines from Piton de Caille oceanites. These researchers also documented high pressures (up to 4·8 kbar) in fluid inclusions in MgO-rich olivine from dunitic enclaves carried by Chisny lavas. In our study, ‘olivine-bearing’ lavas emitted in the peripheral area and dunite and wehrlite enclaves record similar high pressures up to 4·2 kbar (Table 4) in fluid inclusions in olivine crystals whose composition falls in the range between the MgO-richest mode (Fo87–85) measured in Piton de Caille oceanites (Bureau et al., 1998) and the MgO-richest mode found in lavas from the central area (Fo84). In contrast, ‘clinopyroxene-bearing’ lavas emitted in the peripheral area record only intermediate pressures up to 2·9 kbar (Table 4) and their olivine compositions (Fo83·5–81·5) fall between the two main modes found in lavas from the central area. Clinopyroxene barometry of Bellecombe gabbros and of lavas emitted in the central area constrain olivine–clinopyroxene–plagioclase crystallization to an intermediate to shallow depth range (<2·7 ± 1·3 kbar pressure). The 1998 ‘clinopyroxene-bearing’ lavas emitted from the Hudson vent in the central area differ from these observations with unusually MgO-rich olivine (up to Fo88·2) hosting inclusions recording a maximum pressure of c. 4·4 kbar in fluid inclusions (Bureau et al., 1999) and c. 5·1 kbar in melt inclusions (Bureau et al., 1999; Di Muro et al., 2015). In this specific case, this range agrees with the average pressure we estimate from clinopyroxene barometry (3·6 ± 0·9 kbar; Table 4) and highlights the peculiarity of the 1998 ‘clinopyroxene-bearing’ lavas erupted from the Hudson vent with respect to other lavas in the central area (high pressures, MgO-richest olivine, alkaline enrichment).

Magma variability at Piton de la Fournaise

We document variable crystallization pressures of magmas emitted in the peripheral area of PdF (2·7–5·7 kbar), associated with a relatively large geochemical variability (Figs 9–11). Magmas erupted from the northeastern and southeastern rift zones (NERZ, SERZ) are compositionally only slightly variable and overlap with those of lavas emitted in the central EF caldera, in contrast to the original suggestion of Lénat et al. (2012). In contrast, lava compositions from the northwestern rift zone (NWRZ) are compositionally diverse and only partly overlap with lava compositions found in the central area. Previous studies proposed several processes to explain the compositional variability of PdF lavas, which we synthesize in Fig. 13 (see corresponding numbers in circles on the figure): (1) variable melting degree of minor mantle source heterogeneities (Albarède & Tamagnan, 1988; Pietruszka et al., 2009; Di Muro et al., 2014; Vlastélic & Pietruszka, 2016); and/or (2a) a plagioclase effect (Boivin & Bachèlery, 2009; Famin et al., 2009; Di Muro et al., 2015; Valer et al., 2017a); and/or (2b) a clinopyroxene effect (Kornprobst et al., 1979; Albarède et al., 1997); and/or (3) crystal recycling and resorption (Albarède et al., 1997; Salaün et al., 2010); and/or (4) mixing of mantle-derived magmas together with differentiated trachyte melts (Villemant et al., 2009; Salaün et al., 2010) or with low melting-degree partial melts derived from hydrothermally altered cumulates (Pietruszka et al., 2009). In the light of our new results, we now discuss in detail these processes that may explain the geochemical variability in PdF basalts.

Variable melting degree of minor mantle source heterogeneities

We document a small range of 87Sr/86Sr and 143Nd/144Nd isotope ratios in the recent lavas in the peripheral area that is, however, significantly larger than the isotopic variability previously reported for central lavas at PdF (Fisk et al., 1988; Albarède et al., 1997; Bosch et al., 2008; Pietruszka et al., 2009; Di Muro et al., 2014). The slight variations in Sr–Nd isotope compositions correlate only with ratios of variably incompatible elements (Fig. 11) and are consistent with minor mantle source heterogeneities. These can be related either to compositionally distinct components intrinsic to the La Réunion plume itself or to the incorporation of the ambient Indian mantle asthenosphere into the upwelling plume, in agreement with some previous interpretations (Pietruszka et al., 2009; Di Muro et al., 2014; Vlastélic & Pietruszka, 2016). 87Sr/86Sr and 1/Sr are linearly correlated, suggesting a mixing process between two isotopically distinct components [e.g. Petit Cratère (PC) and Chisny (CHI) end-members]. For instance, mixing between melts resulting from variable melting degrees of an isotopically heterogeneous mantle source can produce the observed ranges in Sr–Nd isotopes and part of the variations in incompatible trace element ratios [e.g. Formica Léo (FL); Figs 11 and 13]. This model was previously proposed for the central area to explain the variability observed during the major 2007 eruption episode and during the entire 1998–2006 eruptive period (Di Muro et al., 2014). The occurrence of extensive mixing in the central crustal magma storage system is also supported by the limited range in the Pb isotopic composition of central lavas (Vlastélic et al., 2009).

We argue, however, that slight mantle source effects explain only part of the geochemical variability of melts. In fact, we demonstrate that at PdF transitional magmas with variable compositions of both major (CaO/Al2O3, alkalinity) and trace elements (MREE, HREE) can be emitted within the same vent [e.g. early (CHI) and late stage of Chisny (CHI*); Fig. 9] without variation of Sr–Nd isotopic signature (Figs 11 and 13) and with similar variations in Y (by a factor of 0·3), HREE (by a factor of 0·3–0·4) and highly incompatible element abundances (K2O varies by a factor of 0·3).

Plagioclase fractionation

The average Eu/Eu* ratio is near unity for PdF lavas in both central and peripheral areas (Eu/Eu* = 1·04 ± 0·01), despite significant variations in Al2O3 and CaO/Al2O3 (Figs 9 and 10). This rules out a major role for plagioclase fractionation in the petrogenesis of transitional magmas with alkaline affinity (Famin et al., 2009). Our conclusion is consistent with the rare occurrence of plagioclase (Boivin & Bachèlery, 2009; Di Muro et al., 2015) and the results of the AlphaMELTS modeling, which confines gabbroic evolution to intermediate–shallow depths (Fig. 12). Lavas emitted in the central area and the interstitial glasses from the Bellecombe gabbros best represent this shallow (<3 kbar) gabbroic fractionation and confirm that plagioclase does not play a major role at higher pressures and mainly forms in evolved cool (and/or degassed) melts. Recent reviews have shown that plagioclase microlites or microphenocrysts in lavas emitted in the central area are less anorthitic, and their abundance increases in evolved lavas with MgO <6–7 wt % (Boivin & Bachélery, 2009; Di Muro et al., 2015). More calcic plagioclase (An84) is observed in the Bellecombe gabbros and rare and older plagioclase-rich lavas found at the base of the PdF edifice (Valer et al., 2017a). Modeling suggests that these calcic plagioclase compositions should be in equilibrium with an intermediate melt with 6 wt % MgO over a large pressure range from 1 to 9 kbar for water contents from 0·8 to 1·5 wt % (Lange et al., 2009). However, plagioclase-rich lavas are observed only in specific eruptive phases of PdF that correspond to decreasing magma supply, promoting plagioclase crystallization (Valer et al., 2017a). Experiments on relatively evolved melt compositions from the Kerguelen Islands (5 wt % MgO and 1·2 wt % H2O; Scoates et al. 2006) also demonstrate that plagioclase tends to disappear at a pressure >5 kbar. By combining our AlphaMELTS simulations and these experimental data on similar lavas we may conclude that significant plagioclase fractionation at PdF starts at pressures <3 kbar; that is, at crustal levels. Therefore, the general absence of Eu depletion in peripheral lavas excludes a major role for plagioclase crystallization during PdF magma differentiation. Olivine and clinopyroxene are the dominant fractionating phases over a large range of depths, in accordance with the pyroxene barometry performed in this study.

The role of clinopyroxene in controlling compositional variations

Prior to this study, clinopyroxene phenocrysts were thought to occur only rarely at PdF, except in a prehistoric ankaramite sample (Albarède et al., 1997), in Bellecombe gabbros and in cumulates from the Grand Brulé drillcore (Rancon et al., 1989; Upton et al., 2000). These products were interpreted as the result of shallow magma fractionation. Instead, our new petrological and geochemical data, as well as our modeling results, emphasize the polybaric nature of clinopyroxene fractionation during melt evolution. This explains the CaO/Al2O3 and Sc depletion, and also partially accounts for the MREE–HREE depletion and alkali enrichment observed in most of lavas emitted in the peripheral area [e.g. Chisny (CHI) and Cratère Commerson (CC); Figs 9–12].

A major role for clinopyroxene fractionation has been reported in other ocean island basalt (OIB) suites (e.g. Madeira, El Hierro island; Schwarz et al., 2004; Stroncik et al., 2009) and is widely invoked to explain the decrease in CaO, SiO2, Sc, MREE and HREE, and the increase in FeO and K2O in OIB in general (Naumann & Geist, 1999; Mattsson & Oskarsson, 2005). Interestingly, the distribution of transitional basalt compositions at PdF, with either tholeiitic or alkaline affinity, reflects that of the shield- and post-shield stages at Hawaii (Clague, 1987). There, the Hualalai Volcano shows a temporal evolution from an early tholeiitic shield stage to a post-shield alkaline stage, with lavas that also carry abundant dunite, wehrlite and gabbro xenoliths (Peterson & Moore, 1987). This temporal geochemical evolution has been explained by a decrease in the magma production rate, consequent advanced solidification of shallow magma bodies with limited recharge and migration of the magma storage zone to deeper levels, where clinopyroxene fractionation occurred (Clague, 1987; Chen et al., 1991). However, at PdF, transitional melts with alkaline and tholeiitic affinities are produced synchronously during its whole eruptive history (Albarède et al., 1997; Michon et al., 2015; this study), ruling out a temporal evolution of source conditions, as at Hawaii. The heterogeneities we document in peripheral lavas at PdF could, at least partly, stem from variable depths of magma differentiation following dunitic and wehrlitic trends. For instance, using the composition of natural clinopyroxenes (Salaün et al., 2010; this study) and the melt composition of the 5 April 2007 eruption (similar to the parental magma composition modeled above), we calculate that 10–12 wt % of clinopyroxene crystallization could lead to alkali increase (+0·4 wt % on K2O + Na2O) together with CaO/Al2O3 decrease (–0·2) and explain part of the trace element variability (Figs 9 and 10) observed in lavas emitted in the peripheral area, at constant Sr–Nd isotopic signature (e.g. CHI, CC).

Meanwhile, even if olivine–clinopyroxene differentiation in the uppermost mantle lithosphere is a common process below volcanic islands (Hildner et al., 2011) and plays a major role in the geochemical variability of PdF magmas, we highlight that our AlphaMELTS modeling shows some differences from experimental results. First, recent crystallization experiments on SSB basalt compositions have shown that clinopyroxene may crystallize before olivine at pressures higher than 3–4 kbar (Brugier, 2016), whereas our study suggests that at all pressures (up to 9 kbar in this study), olivine is the first phase that crystallizes in PdF magmas, followed by clinopyroxene. The evolved composition of the starting material used for the experimental investigations (MgO = 7·8 wt %; Brugier, 2016) contrasts with the composition of the starting melt used in our modeling (MgO >10·3 wt %). The widespread mild alkali enrichment together with low CaO/Al2O3 ratios that we document in bulk-rocks and in matrix glasses of peripheral eruptive lavas is not observed in the most magnesian melt inclusions found in olivine (MgO >10 wt %; Fig. 9a). This suggests that these compositional features are attained later in the differentiation process and this justifies the use of a more primitive (MgO >10 wt %) starting composition in our model compared with the experiments. Second, our modeling does not reproduce the crystallization of diopside that we observe in ultramafic enclaves and gabbros. This observation could either reflect the limitations of the AlphaMELTS code or be evidence for distinct melt evolution processes involved in forming ultramafic enclaves and gabbros.

Crystal recycling and resorption

In ‘olivine-bearing’ lavas from peripheral eruptions there is an extensive recirculation of olivine crystals, as shown by the common presence of clusters of polyhedral crystals (Fig. 2f), abundance of wehrlite and dunite enclaves (Fig. 3a and b), polymodal forsterite distribution (Fig. 4b), and low Ca contents in olivine overlapping that found in the olivine of ultramafic enclaves (Fig. 5b). The incorporation of 5–10 wt % olivine can explain the observed discrepancy between the composition of matrix glasses and bulk-rocks in ‘olivine-bearing’ lavas (e.g. CHI in Fig. 13) as previously reported (Albarède et al., 1997; Salaün et al., 2010). An interesting result of our study is that ‘olivine-bearing’ lavas from peripheral vents do not contain pyroxene phenocrysts despite (1) large amounts of wehrlite enclaves and olivine antecrysts and (2) geochemical evidence for clinopyroxene fractionation (alkaline affinity and depletion in CaO, SiO2, Sc, MREE, HREE). This represents the ‘pyroxene paradox’ (Francis, 1986) and suggests the role of ‘cryptic’ clinopyroxene fractionation.

With respect to the results discussed above, we propose that clinopyroxene crystals can be fractionated and potentially resorbed and redissolved by mafic melts during their ascent, as also proposed for Hawaii (Frey et al., 1990; Wanless et al., 2006) and Iceland (Furman et al., 1991; Mattsson & Oskarsson, 2005). At PdF, petrological arguments in favor of deep clinopyroxene resorption were also previously presented by Fretzdorff & Haase (2002) for old submarine lavas carrying MgO-rich olivine (Fo90). The 2005 olivine-rich lavas in the central area also contain resorbed sector-zoned clinopyroxenes (Welsch et al., 2009), and we observed partially resorbed clinopyroxenes in gabbroic cumulates from the Bellecombe Ash Member.

To evaluate clinopyroxene stability conditions during magma ascent and storage we simulated the reaction between (1) a solid assemblage of olivine–clinopyroxene formed at 6 kbar and 1190°C (predicted by the modeling of CHI–CHI* paths from an initial melt with 10 wt % MgO and 1 wt % H2O; Fig. 13) and (2) the residual melt (8 wt % MgO; 1·18 wt % H2O) at 1190°C ponding at 4 kbar; that is, the depth of the underplating layer (Supplementary Data Electronic Appendix 5, Simulation 3). AlphaMELTS modeling suggests that clinopyroxene should indeed dissolve rapidly when the assemblage is stored at shallower pressures. Similarly, experimental studies on basaltic compositions at a pressure and temperature range relevant for PdF (e.g. Shaw & Dingwell, 2008; Chen & Zhang, 2009) have shown that the dissolution rate of clinopyroxene is more sensitive to temperature (i.e. degree of superheating) and melt composition (volatile content increase, silica–alkali enrichment, and calcium depletion) in contrast to olivine. Interestingly, an experiment at 1250°C and 5 kbar (Chen & Zhang, 2009; close to the conditions discussed in this study) on a basaltic melt showed that clinopyroxene dissolution is at least two times faster than olivine dissolution and may occur in a time span as short as a few days. These studies are consistent with our results and demonstrate that (1) melts generating ‘olivine-bearing’ lavas are generally richer in MgO and thus hotter than those generating ‘clinopyroxene-bearing’ lavas (Helz & Thornber, 1987) and (2) early deep olivine–clinopyroxene fractionation tends to increase the water contents of the residual melts, together with increasing the alkali contents. The clinopyroxene resorption process would thus be favored by magma storage at intermediate depths, where more evolved and possibly slightly water-enriched magmas may stagnate and/or mix with a more primitive and hotter melt depressing the clinopyroxene liquidus. Conversely, fast magma ascent without intermediate storage may favor the survival of clinopyroxene–olivine equilibrium, as observed in ‘clinopyroxene-bearing’ lavas that display fast-growth crystal textures and no evidence of re-equilibration processes (e.g. comparison between fluid inclusions and pyroxene barometry). Our results confirm that crystal recycling and resorption in basaltic melts also contribute to the geochemical variability of the magmas erupted (Costa & Dungan, 2005).

Mixing of mantle-derived magmas together with differentiated trachytic melts and/or with low melting-degree partial melts derived from hydrothermally altered cumulates

With respect to the effect of the magmatic processes described above, we note that the composition of some eruptive products may not be related to either mantle source heterogeneities or crystal fractionation. This is the case, for instance, for some lavas from the late stage of the Chisny eruptive activity (e.g. CHI*) that are much more enriched in incompatible trace elements (Fig. 10c), but have similar Sr–Nd isotopic compositions and CaO/Al2O3 ratios (Figs 10c and 13c) compared with those emitted during the first phases at Chisny (e.g. CHI).

Such ‘anomalous’ enrichment in incompatible elements in PdF melts was previously reported in the 1998 ‘clinopyroxene-bearing’ lavas erupted from the Hudson vent and in some other rare lavas in the central area (Bureau et al., 1998; Pietruszka et al., 2009; Salaün et al., 2010). In the case of the 1998 ‘clinopyroxene-bearing’ Hudson lavas, which are representative of the AbG signature (Famin et al., 2009), mixing between compositionally distinct, mafic and evolved melts was proposed (Figs 9–11; Salaün et al., 2010). For instance, mixing of 6 wt % of a trachytic melt (Salaün et al., 2010) into an olivine-bearing melt, such as produced during the 5 April 2007 eruption, may explain most of the chemical variability in major and trace elements of these lavas (Fig. 13). This is also consistent with the observed Eu depletion and decrease in CaO/Al2O3 (Fig. 10b).

Although some lavas erupted from peripheral vents (CHI*, DP) share some similarities with the 1998 ‘clinopyroxene-bearing’ lavas (AbG) such as CaO/Al2O3 depletion and alkaline and incompatible trace element enrichment (Figs 9 and 10), they strongly differ in their petrological characteristics (Table 1), distinct olivine compositions (Figs 5 and 6), the absence of negative Eu anomalies (Fig. 10b) and different MREE/LREE (light REE) ratios (Fig. 11a). Mixing with a strongly differentiated (and low-temperature–high-viscosity) trachytic melt thus appears unlikely. On the other hand, Pietruszka et al. (2009) suggested that contamination with small amounts of low melting-degree partial melts derived from hydrothermally altered cumulates may explain the chemistry of some unusual historical lavas in the central area. To test this hypothesis, we have simulated (Figs 10c and 13c) contamination of a melt with a low CaO/Al2O3 ratio (after clinopyroxene fractionation; e.g. CHI) by partial melts derived from wehrlite cumulates (‘94.G1’ with about 60% of clinopyroxene, 35% of olivine and 5% of interstitial melt; Upton et al., 2000). We have preferred wehrlite cumulates instead of gabbroic cumulates because contaminated melts do not show Eu depletion (e.g. CHI*; Fig. 10b). For this simulation we use the melt–olivine–clinopyroxene partition coefficients of Salters & Longhi (1999) and Adam & Green (2006) and assumed simple batch melting (Shaw, 1970). We calculate that less than 1% of partial melting of such wehrlitic cumulates is sufficient to produce a melt with CaO/Al2O3 = 0·56, Th = 12 ppm and Th/Yb = 7·1 and a major element composition close to the interstitial glasses from the Bellecombe gabbro cumulates (Upton et al., 2000). Successive mixing between the composition of low CaO/Al2O3 (0·71) CHI basaltic melts and 5% of such a partial melt fits the composition of the CHI* melts (Figs 10c and 13c). This amount of mixed partial melt is similar to those calculated by Pietruszka et al. (2009).

We suggest that the generation of low-degree partial melts from cumulates may be favored by the intrusion of ‘olivine-bearing’ magmas into the cumulate pile at the depth of the mantle–crust underplating layer, consistent with evidence for abundant inclusions of cumulates and recycled crystals. With respect to the above considerations on clinopyroxene stability in PdF melts, this supports the role of clinopyroxene resorption in producing some contaminant liquids and constitutes a reasonable explanation for the variability observed in some incompatible trace elements, at constant Sr–Nd isotopic signature, at similar major element compositions.

Linking petrological and geophysical observations

Our study, combined with recent geophysical (Michon et al., 2015) and geochemical (Liuzzo et al., 2015; Boudoire et al., 2017) data, provides further insights into the plumbing system of PdF (Fig. 14).

Fig. 14

Conceptual model of the deep plumbing system of Piton de La Fournaise showing magma transfer and storage below the NW rift zone (see text for explanation). Large filled rectangles represent the main depth ranges constrained by barometric data, obtained from fluid inclusion analysis (red for mantle pressures; blue for crustal pressures). Partially transparent rectangles represent the pressure range recorded by fluid inclusions. Lateral magma migration in the upper mantle is based on a review of recent seismic data (Michon et al., 2015). Fast ascent of deep magmas below the NWRZ permits the preservation of a deeper chemical signature and represents a major source of potential volcanic hazard on the densely populated volcano flanks. Pressure–depth relations are from Table 3.

Open in new tabDownload slide

At La Réunion, the occurrence of a deep zone of magma ponding within the mantle lithosphere at 30 km b.s.l. (c. 8–10 kbar pressure) has been proposed on the basis of seismic tomography (Fig. 14a;Charvis et al., 1999; Fontaine et al., 2015). This depth range overlaps with that of the deepest seismic swarms (c. 30 km b.s.l.) that started to be recorded just after the major 2007 eruption (Massin et al., 2011). This deep level may also correspond to a level of neutral buoyancy, allowing deep magma stagnation and the first stage of high-pressure olivine–clinopyroxene crystallization to proceed as proposed by Albarède et al. (1997). Rare MgO-rich olivine (Fo>88) and high-pressure clinopyroxene documented in submarine lavas by Fretzdorff & Haase (2002) may derive from this early, deep stage of differentiation. The occurrence of a deep level of melt differentiation in the lithospheric mantle has also been reported for other OIB suites and could facilitate the early evolution of melt from tholeiitic to transitional compositions (Naumann & Geist, 1999; Stroncik et al., 2009). Between these high pressures and the lower (maximum) pressures (c. 4·8–5·7 kbar) preserved in some olivine-hosted fluid and melt inclusions (Table 4; Fig. 13) there is a gap for which there is no pressure record, which could testify to fast magma ascent, with limited cooling and crystallization, from the deep reservoir at 30 km towards the base of the oceanic crust. The pressure record of 3·9–4·2 kbar by olivine-hosted fluid inclusions from ‘olivine-bearing’ lavas erupted in the peripheral area (3·9–4·2 ± 0·7 kbar) is consistent with magma ponding and fractionation between 15 and 10 km b.s.l. A similar pressure (4 kbar) recorded by fluid inclusions in MgO-rich olivine antecrysts hosted in ‘clinopyroxene-bearing’ lavas confirms stagnation and crystallization at the crust–mantle boundary (Fig. 14b). In 1996 and 2014, clusters of seismic events were identified at this intermediate depth (15–16 km b.s.l.; 5 kbar) close to the NW border of EF caldera. These events marked the onset of unrest leading to the central volcanic activity in 1998 and 2014 (Battaglia et al., 2005; Boudoire et al., 2017).

A <3 km thick layer of dense crustal underplated rocks was identified at the depth range from 10 to 13 km b.s.l., based on seismic studies, corresponding to a pressure of 3·3–4·2 kbar (Charvis et al., 1999; Gallart et al., 1999; Fontaine et al., 2015; Fig. 14c). At least some of the dunitic and wehrlitic cumulate lithic fragments from Chisny may derive from this layer. The absence of clinopyroxene phenocrysts in ‘olivine-bearing’ lavas emitted in the peripheral area and carrying and recycling abundant wehrlites and dunites suggests that the underplating layer might also be the zone in which resorption of clinopyroxene occurs. Fast ascent from this stagnation level is supported by voluminous peripheral cones that contain large (>10 cm), dense xenoliths. Fast ascent rates were also proposed by Sigmarsson et al. (2005) based on short-lived radionuclide disequilibria in NWRZ lavas. The frequency of recent volcanic cones along the narrow NWRZ (<50 kyr; one eruption every 200 yr; Michon et al., 2015) suggests that magma ascent is facilitated along zones of weakness that, according to Bachèlery (1981) and Michon et al. (2007), may be related to the structural inheritance of the underlying oceanic lithosphere. These observations imply that pathways of fast magma ascent from the upper mantle can open below the western volcano flank.

‘Clinopyroxene-bearing’ basalts (2·4–2·7 ± 0·7 kbar on average) and the Bellecombe gabbros represent magma storage at intermediate pressures at a deep crustal level close to the Moho. Rapid magma ascent from such relatively deep levels can occur not only in the peripheral but also in the central summit area (Fig. 14d). This pressure range is consistent with a high concentration of abundant micro-earthquakes observed during the seismic swarm of March 1998 preceding the eruption of the 1998 ‘clinopyroxene-bearing’ basalts at the Hudson vent (e.g. Battaglia et al., 2005; Michon et al., 2015). These seismic events trace a subvertical seismic zone from 7·5 km depth towards the summit and represent magma ascent within the main central conduit system. Many geochemical and geophysical studies have focused on the shallow (crustal) part of the central plumbing system of PdF (<1 kbar; Aki & Ferrazzini, 2000; Battaglia et al., 2005; Fukushima et al., 2005; Famin et al., 2009; Di Muro et al., 2014, 2015). These studies emphasize the presence of small-volume magma reservoirs at or above sea level (Nercessian et al., 1996; Battaglia et al., 2005; Sigmarsson et al., 2005; Famin et al., 2009; Peltier et al., 2009; Welsch et al., 2009; Vlastélic & Pietruszka, 2016). Low pressures recorded by most olivine-hosted melt and fluid inclusions in lavas from the central area and the rare occurrence of low Ti/Al pyroxenes in these lavas support these interpretations. Moreover, the compositions of most magmas that were processed in and erupted from the central plumbing system follow a gabbroic differentiation trend that is confined to shallow depths (e.g. Bellecombe gabbros; <2·7 kbar). This shallow plumbing system is conceived of as a network of magma pockets and dykes (Albarède et al., 1997; Di Muro et al., 2014) hosting differentiated and differentiating magmas that feed the eruptions of the summit cone but can also erupt laterally on the NE and SE rift zones (Fig. 14e).

CONCLUSIONS

Extrusive and intrusive products recently (<5 kyr) emitted on the western flank of Piton de la Fournaise (PdF) reveal petrological and geochemical variations that provide new insights into the deep magma plumbing system, and link the central and peripheral magmatic systems of this highly active volcano.

We document chemical and Sr–Nd isotopic variations in erupted lavas, closely associated in time and space, from both the peripheral and the central area of the volcano. The lavas emitted in the peripheral area exhibit Sr–Nd isotopic variations that overlap (and exceed) those of lavas emitted in the central area. Sr–Nd isotopic variations and their correlation with high to moderately incompatible element ratios suggest melting of small-scale heterogeneities in the mantle source region. To better identify possible end-members and their origin in the mantle further work is required. As an example, it is unknown whether the Pb isotopic composition of peripheral lavas correlates with Sr–Nd variations. Apart from variations in the mantle source, mixing between basaltic melt end-members with distinct Sr-isotope signatures, and variable ratios of incompatible trace elements, this study highlights compositional variations caused by polybaric clinopyroxene crystallization–resorption and olivine crystallization–recycling to produce the major element compositional variability of PdF basalts.

Barometric data highlight the early magma crystallization and differentiation below La Réunion Island at mantle depths (8–10 kbar), whereas magma evolution is enhanced during ponding over a pressure range of 3–6 kbar and at shallower levels within the volcanic edifice itself (Fig. 14). The scarcity of MgO-rich olivine (Fo>88) in erupted magmas and the absence of true primitive compositions in subaerial lavas is thus well explained by early, deep (>8 kbar) fractionation of primary melts. Deep (3–6 kbar) cotectic crystallization of olivine (Fo<88) and low Ti/Al clinopyroxene controls the composition of most ‘olivine-bearing’ lavas emitted in the peripheral area. These basalts record the geochemical signature of high-pressure olivine–clinopyroxene fractionation at lithospheric mantle depths, but lack pyroxene phenocrysts despite the presence of abundant wehrlite enclaves and olivine antecrysts. This discrepancy is thought to result from clinopyroxene resorption during magma storage at intermediate depths, where more evolved and possibly slightly water-enriched magmas may pond, and/or by mixing with more primitive and hotter melts that depress the clinopyroxene liquidus. In addition, some of these magmas show evidence of contamination with small amounts (up to 5%) of low-degree partial melts derived from cumulates. Conversely, ‘clinopyroxene-bearing’ lavas from the peripheral area of Piton de la Fournaise display widespread textures of fast crystal growth and record olivine–clinopyroxene crystallization at intermediate crustal depths (3 kbar), followed by rapid magma ascent that is essential to prevent complete clinopyroxene dissolution. The conduit system centered below the EF caldera feeds the NE and SE rift zones with relatively evolved magmas (<7–8 wt % MgO). These basalts, produced by shallow ‘gabbroic differentiation’ (<3 kbar and in most cases <1 kbar), contain MgO-poor olivine (Fo<84) and high Ti/Al clinopyroxenes.

In this study, we argue for multiple magma ponding zones within the uppermost mantle beneath PdF and within the crust, with potential mixing between slightly isotopically distinct melts. We demonstrate that fast ascent of deep-seated magmas occurs over both the central area and the densely populated volcano flanks, with major implications in terms of volcanic hazard. These new findings should be carefully taken into account in volcano monitoring and for civil protection.
